window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : MOTION UNDER GRAVITY","question":"You are provided with a grooved inclined plane, a solid sphere, stop watch and other necessary materials.  (i) Place the pile of paper towels at the tail end of the inclined plane to stop the sphere from rolling off the table.  (ii) Release the sphere from a point at a distance  D  = 140 cm from the tail end of the inclined plane.  (iii) Determine the average time t taken by the sphere to cover this distance.  (iv) Evaluate W = Dt\\frac{D}{t}tD\u200b.  (v) Evaluate V = 2W  (vi) Repeat the procedure for  four other values of D = 120 cm, 100 cm, 80 cm, and 60 cm respectively.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph of V on the vertical axis and t on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope,  s, of the graph.   (x) What is the significance of  s?  (xi) State  two  precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    D(cm)t1(s)t2(s)t = t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)W = Dt\\frac{D}{t}tD\u200b(cm/s)V = 2W (cm/s)140.04.505.004.75029.47458.948120.04.204.404.30027.90755.814100.04.003.803.98025.64151.28280.03.803.503.65021.91843.83660.03.203.403.30018.18236.364        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 57.5\u2212404.5\u22123.375\\frac{57.5-40}{4.5-3.375}4.5\u22123.37557.5\u221240\u200b = 17.51.125\\frac{17.5}{1.125}1.12517.5\u200b = 15.56    The slope s represents the acceleration due to gravity in the experiment.    Precautions:   1. I ensured the grooved inclined plane was securely set up and stable to prevent any unwanted movement during the experiment, which could affect the sphere's motion and the accuracy of time measurements.    2. I released the sphere gently from the designated point without pushing it to avoid introducing additional forces that could alter its velocity and the recorded time.    3. I ensured the paper towels at the tail end of the inclined plane were adequately positioned to stop the sphere without causing it to bounce or roll off, ensuring accurate measurement of the distance covered.    4. I used a precise stopwatch to measure the time taken by the sphere, starting the timer exactly when the sphere was released and stopping it as soon as it reached the designated endpoint.    5. I repeated the measurements for each distance multiple times to account for any inconsistencies and reduce random errors in the average time calculated.    6. I carefully recorded all data in a clear and organized manner to avoid confusion and ensure accurate tabulation of results for graph plotting.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Write the equation for the velocity ratio of an inclined plane, giving the meaning of the symbols used. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"VelocityRatio(VR)=Length of the inclined plane (L)Height of the inclined plane (h)    This equation tells us how many times the distance the effort moves is greater than the distance the load moves.    L: Length of the inclined plane: This is the distance along the slope of the inclined plane.    h: Height of the inclined plane: This is the vertical distance between the higher and lower ends of the inclined plane.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"An object of mass 5 kg is placed on a plane inclined at an angle of 30\u00b0 to the horizontal. Calculate the force on the object perpendicular to the plane when the object is at rest. (g = 10m-2). [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p and with the unit e.g 123.123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"mass of the object = 5 kg    angle of inclination = 30\u00b0    acceleration due to gravity = 10ms-2        F = mgcos \u03b8    F = 5 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 cos 30\u00b0    F = 5 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 0.8860    F = 43.3 N","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"You are provided with an illuminated object, converging lens, screen, meter rule, and other necessary materials.  (i) Measure and record the size  ao of the illuminated object.  (ii) Place the object  O  and the screen  S on opposite sides of the converging lens L.  (iii) Set the distance between the object and the lens U = 30 cm.  (iv)  Adjust the screen until a sharp image of the illuminated object is obtained on the screen  (v) Measure and record the size aa of the image.  (vi) Evaluate m =  aao\\frac{a}{a_{o}}ao\u200ba\u200b     (vii) Repeat the procedure for  four other values of  U = 35 cm, 40 cm, 45 cm, and 50 cm respectively.  (viii) Tabulate your readings.  (ix) Plot a graph with  m-1  on the vertical axis and  U on the horizontal axis.  (x)  Determine the slope,  s, of the graph, and intercept,  c, on the vertical axis.  (xi) Determine the value of  U for which m\u22121 = 0.  (xii) State  two precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values / Observation    ao = 1.5 cm    u(cm)a(cm)m =aao\\frac{a}{a_{o}}ao\u200ba\u200bm-130.02.21.4670.68235.01.51.0001.00040.01.20.8001.25045.00.90.6001.66750.00.70.4672.141        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 2.05\u22120.850\u221232.5\\frac{2.05-0.8}{50-32.5}50\u221232.52.05\u22120.8\u200b = 1.2517.5\\frac{1.25}{17.5}17.51.25\u200b = 0.07    Intercept, c = -1.52    when m-1  = 0, U = 21.20 cm    Precautions:  1. I ensured parallax error was avoided by positioning my eyes directly in line with the metre rule when taking measurements.  2. I maintained a consistent light source intensity to avoid variations in image clarity on the screen.  3. I took repeated readings to minimize random errors and improve accuracy.  4. I ensured the lens and screen were kept steady and free from vibrations during measurements.  5. I ensured that the lens was clean to prevent any distortion or scattering of light.  6. I carefully aligned the object, lens, and screen along a straight path to obtain a sharp, clear image.  7. I avoided unnecessary movements around the setup to prevent vibrations that could affect the image stability.  8. I verified the distance settings on the metre rule to ensure accuracy at each reading point.  9. I kept the surrounding area free from drafts that could shift the lens or screen and affect measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Using your graph, determine the value of m for which U = 37 cm. [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"For a distance U = 37 cm, the corresponding value of m-1, as accurately determined from the graph, is 1.133.    Since m-1 = 1.133    \u2234 m = 11.133\\frac{1}{1.133}1.1331\u200b = 0.88","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Sketch a diagram to illustrate how a converging lens may be used to produce a real diminished image of an object. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The object is placed beyond 2F1","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a potentiometer  AB , a 10 \u03a9 standard resistor  R, a battery of emf 4.5 V, a jockey  J, and other necessary materials.    (i) Connect a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Close key  K . Without  J making contact with  AB , read and record the ammeter reading  I . Open the key.  (iii) Use the jockey to make contact with  AB at the 20 cm mark such that AJ = x = 20 cm. Close the key, read and record the ammeter reading I.  (iv) Evaluate x-1.  (v) Repeat the procedure for values of x = 35 cm, 45 cm, 60 cm, and 80 cm respectively.  (vi) Tabulate your readings.  (vii) Plot a graph with  x-1 on the vertical axis and I on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0, 0).  (viii) Determine the slope,  s, of the graph.  (ix) From your graph, determine the value  Io of   I1 for which x-1 = 0.  (x) Evaluate IoI\\frac{I_{o}}{I}IIo\u200b\u200b.  (xi) State  two precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"I = 0.36 A    Table of values / Observation    x(cm)I(A)x-1(cm-1)20.01.140.05035.00.900.02945.00.840.02260.00.780.01780.00.660.013        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.045\u22120.01631.1\u22120.75\\frac{0.045-0.0163}{1.1-0.75}1.1\u22120.750.045\u22120.0163\u200b = 0.02870.35\\frac{0.0287}{0.35}0.350.0287\u200b = 0.082 cm-1A-1    From the graph,  when x-1 = 0, Io of I1 = 0.54 A    Evaluate IoI1\\frac{I_{o}}{I_{1}}I1\u200bIo\u200b\u200b = 0.540.36\\frac{0.54}{0.36}0.360.54\u200b = 1.5    Precautions:  1. I ensured the key was open when readings were not being taken to prevent draining the battery.  2. I checked that all connections were tight to maintain consistent current flow.  3. I avoided parallax error by viewing the potentiometer scale directly from the front.  4. I carefully avoided dragging the jockey along the potentiometer wire to prevent damage or inaccuracies.  5. I ensured the ammeter was properly calibrated before starting the experiment.  6. I maintained a stable surface for all apparatus to prevent unwanted movement during measurements.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Define emf of a battery. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The e.m.f. (electromotive force) of a battery is the total energy per unit charge supplied by the battery when no current flows through the circuit. It represents the maximum potential difference between the battery terminals and is responsible for driving electric charge around a complete circuit.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2014>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2014","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A cell  X of emf 1.018 V is balanced by a length of 50.0 cm on a potentiometer wire. Another cell  Y is balanced by a length of 75.0 cm on the same wire. Calculate the emf of  Y. [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p and with the unit e.g 12.12 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"EX = 1.018 V    LX = 50.0 cm    LY = 75.0 cm    EY = ?    Using the formula:    EXEY\\frac{E_{X}}{E_{Y}}EY\u200bEX\u200b\u200b = LXLY\\frac{L_{X}}{L_{Y}}LY\u200bLX\u200b\u200b    1.018EY\\frac{1.018}{E_{Y}}EY\u200b1.018\u200b = 5075\\frac{50}{75}7550\u200b    EY = 1.527 V","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];